The trigger condition is whenever ~ is dealt damage... as opposed to whenever ~ is dealt damage by a source....

There's a subtle difference between them. The former only cares if the creature was dealt damage, not by what or by how many or how much so only triggers a single time regardless of how many sources of damage deal it damage at that time. The latter cares what deals damage and will trigger multiple times if simultaneous damage comes from multiple sources.

If you want a parallel, think of whenever ~ becomes blocked... vs whenever ~ becomes blocked by a creature.... The first only triggers once regardless of how many creatures block, the second triggers for each creature that blocks.

First strike and double strike create two combat damage steps so potentially two distinct moments of damage that the enrage trigger could trigger for.
